    Letter of the Latin alphabet
    \n
    This article needs additional citations for verification. Please help improve this article by adding citations to reliable sources. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.
    Find sources: "Turned v" \xe2\x80\x93 news \xc2\xb7 newspapers \xc2\xb7 books \xc2\xb7 scholar \xc2\xb7 JSTOR     (December 2009) (Learn how and when to remove this template message)
    \n
    "\xca\x8c" redirects here. Not to be confused with \xe2\x88\xa7, \xce\xbb, \xe4\xba\xba, \xe3\x85\x85, or ^.
    \n
    \xc9\x85
    \xc9\x85 \xca\x8c
    Usage
    Writing systemLatin script
    TypeAlphabetic and Logographic
    Unicode codepointU+0245, U+028C
    History
    Development
    • \xc9\x85 \xca\x8c
    Other
    This article contains phonetic transcriptions in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA). For an introductory guide on IPA symbols, see Help:IPA. For the distinction between [ ], / / and ⟨ ⟩, see IPA \xc2\xa7 Brackets and transcription delimiters.
    \n

    Turned v (majuscule: \xc9\x85, minuscule: \xca\x8c) is a letter of the Latin alphabet, based on a turned form of the letter V.\n

    It is used in the orthographies of Dan, Ch\xe2\x80\x99ol, Nankina, Northern Tepehu\xc3\xa1n, Temne, Oneida, and Wounaan and also some orthographies of Ibibio.[1]\n

    Its lowercase is used in the International Phonetic Alphabet to represent an open-mid back unrounded vowel, the vowel in plus in many dialects of English.\n

    Despite the similarity in appearance, the letter has no connection to the Greek \xce\x9b, Chinese/Japanese \xe4\xba\xba or Korean \xe3\x85\x85.\n

    \n\n
